<TITLE> Blue chips drive stocks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 27 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks finished higher for a third day on Sunday, driven by blue chips. The market witnessed even buying and selling with mutual funds and blue chips topping investors' buying basket. Other sectors closed mixed. The benchmark DGEN or general index opened the day with a sharp rise and maintained a stable curve across the day before falling towards the end. It edged up 7.02 points or 0.24 percent to 2885.10. The DSI or all-share price index ended 6.75 points or 0.27 percent higher on 2498.68. The blue-chip DSE-20 finished at 2666.76, gaining 30.62 points or 1.16 percent. Indices on Chittagong Stock Exchange ended lower as shares of banks, ceramics and ICT witnessed huge losses. The CSCX or selective categories index fell 23.59 points or 0.41 percent to close on 5668.73. The CASPI or all-share price index closed at 8796.95, losing 39.78 points or 0.45 percent. The bourse's blue-chip CSE-30 declined 20.64 points, or 0.26 percent, to end on 7848.48. An official with brokerage house IDLC Securities told bdnews24.com mutual funds and the blue chips enjoyed buying while other sectors closed mixed. Meanwhile, ICB AMCL 2nd NRB Mutual Fund closed at Tk 190 on its debut on the bourses Sunday. ICB Asset Management Company, a subsidiary of Investment Corporation of Bangladesh (ICB), floated the Tk 100 crore mutual fund in May, targeting non-resident Bangladeshis. Local investors got shares of Tk 20 crore in the mutual fund. The face value of the MF is Tk 100 per share. Turnover from 23,143,852 shares traded on the DSE crept up to Tk 3.70 billion from Thursday's Tk 3.42 billion. Advancers beat decliners 125 to 101, with three issues holding steady. Turnover on the port city bourse reached Tk 547.34 million, with 5,011,586 shares changing hands, up from Tk 516.02 million on last week's closing day. Of the traded 144 issues, 62 gained, 77 lost and five remained unchanged. "The day saw almost equal buying and selling. The rise in blue chips in the morning session saved the day from falling indices," investment consultant Bashir Ahmed told bdnews24.com. The sell-offs by retail investors were still observed with institutional buying holding up the indices, added Bashir who is with brokerage house Stocks & Bonds. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed echoed Bashir. "Retail investors are still hesitating to trade out of fear." He asked investors not to panic due to falling indices. "Ups and downs are the nature of capital market," added the prime bourse's top official. Turnover leader Keya Cosmetics continued to gain, rising 4.45 percent to end on Tk 96.20. Second in line, UCBL eroded the previous day's losses to finish 6.07 percent higher at Tk 6713.50. Square Pharmaceuticals edged down 0.85 percent to Tk 4168.25. BATBC advanced 5.79 percent to Tk 244.50. Beximco Pharma finished 2.68 percent lower at Tk 112.40, following Thursday's gains. Among the other scrips on the turnover boardLanka Bangla Finance, ACI and Beximcoalso declined. Islami Bank and ICB AMCL 2nd NRB Mutual Fund advanced. bdn
